article.description: Candice Wiggins overcame a slow start on offense to score 20 points and Stanford (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) won its 12th straight game with a 67-53 victory over Arizona State.
article.headline: Wiggins powers Cardinal past Sun Devils
article.linkText: Cardinal rule: Wiggins, Stanford win 12th straight
article.story:
STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Candice Wiggins has a long list of things she wants to do better, even though she's doing an awful lot right.

Stanford's freshman star overcame a slow start on offense to score 20 points and the Cardinal (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) won their 12th straight game with a 67-53 victory over Arizona State on Saturday.

Wiggins, a candidate for Pac-10 freshman of the year and player of the year honors, struggled to finish on drives to the hoop early and started the game 2-for-8. But she scored 15 of her points in the second half and finished 6-of-13 from the field.

She made all eight of her free throws; had five rebounds, three steals and two assists; and scored seven points during a decisive 13-2 second-half run.

When Wiggins arrived at Stanford in the fall, she wasn't sure she'd find success at this level right away. Everybody else knew better.

And coach Tara VanDerveer is thrilled about how quickly Wiggins has adjusted to the college game.

"I definitely didn't expect to come in and dominate," said Wiggins, among the most sought-after recruits in the country last year. "I grew up watching Stanford and the Pac-10. I just have to go out and play as hard as I can. Confidence is probably the key word. You never know until you start playing. I see myself as so raw right now."

Brooke Smith added 15 points and five rebounds and Kelley Suminski 12 points as Stanford (21-2, 12-1 Pac-10) extended its home winning streak to 19 games and won its 35th straight conference game in Maples Pavilion.

Kylan Loney scored 13 points for a Sun Devils team that constantly tries to control the pace of the game but couldn't make enough big shots.

"We just got a little soft," Arizona State coach Charli Turner Thorne said. "I think probably the biggest thing we need to work on as a team is limiting those let-ups and continuing to talk to each other."

Wiggins scored a career-high 31 points at Arizona State last month.

"That young lady's intensity is just incredible," Turner Thorne said. "You think as a freshman you can kind of take her out of the game, but you can't. She will find a way to hurt you."

Emily Westerberg added 10 points for Arizona State (15-7, 7-5), which had gone 5-2 since losing to Stanford 68-57 on Jan. 7 in Tempe. The Cardinal have won 24 of the last 27 meetings in the series.

Stanford hasn't lost a Pac-10 home game since a 62-59 defeat against Southern California on March 1, 2001. The Cardinal have won 54 of their last 57 games at home.

"In some ways, I thought we were a little more aggressive than we have been," Loney said. "We knew they had improved since the last time we played them but that we also had improved. Rebounding killed us."

The Cardinal entered Saturday's game averaging a 20.6-point margin of victory during their winning streak, including a 91-74 victory over rival Arizona on Thursday night.

They used a full-court press from the start in an effort to rattle the Sun Devils, who thrive on a disruptive, pressure style of play themselves.

Arizona State forward Kristen Kovesdy, the team's second-leading scorer at 11.3 points per game, came in shooting a conference-best 61.5 percent but was held to eight points.

Stanford led 11-2, forced five turnovers in the first five minutes and limited the Sun Devils to only four shots during that span. Arizona State missed its first eight field-goal attempts and didn't have a basket until Westerberg's 3-pointer at 10:43.

The Sun Devils made two more 3s to pull within 16-13, but Stanford answered with a 14-9 spurt -- seven by Smith -- to end the half for a 30-22 lead at the break.

VanDerveer considers this one of the most special teams she's had during her 19 seasons at Stanford, and a No. 1 seed in the NCAA Tournament is seeming like a real possibility.

"I thought this had the feel of a tournament game," VanDerveer said. "Our team has played in close games a lot. It's good for us to have these games. I think they're an NCAA team."

The Sun Devils already have wins over ranked teams Connecticut and Georgia.
